passages.text: First Take Q225: Guidance cut for 2025 but purely on FX and closure of busineses, which will likely impact the shares this morning; Weakness a buying opportunity

Our Take: Delivery Hero reported what we consider to be a good set of Q225 results, with revenues beating by \(4\%\) and GMV in line. Group EBITDA for H1 came in \(7\%\) ahead of consensus (company- collated) expectations (see tables below). The focus will be on FY25 guidance which was cut (see below) driven by FX effects (mostly Korea but also MENA which is pegged to the USD). The company also adjusted for the close- down of businesses in Thailand and a small part of Glovo Spain. Lower guidance (and a likely \(8\%\) cut to EBITDA for FY25) are likely to have a negative impact on the shares this morning at open, but we highlight that on an underlying basis (i.e. ex FX, ex business closures) guidance was not cut and would have been achieved. Also, trading conditions in Asia are improving and the company generated its first positive EBIT (€5m) in H1. As highlighted earlier, we continue to believe in our "JustiFoodHero" theme (note here) and view Delivery Hero as having (still) strategic value for Prosus, with the sell- down potentially re- assessed once the Just Eat transaction has closed. We reiterate our OW on the name and see a buying opportunity on any weakness today.

Noteworthy Areas: 1) Overall Q2 group GMV was up \(11\%\) YoY on a like- for- like basis to €12.2bn, with MENA GMV growing by \(26\%\) driven by Talabat and Hungerstation, while Asia was down \(2\%\) on a like- for- like basis, albeit improving sequentially from Q1 (- 7% on a like- for- like basis); 2) Total segment revenue grew \(27\%\) YoY on a like- for- like basis with strong performance across regions driven by the combination of a unified platform and localised execution; 3) Management highlighted positive momentum in Asia with a return to growth in APAC and enhanced growth dynamics in South Korea; 4) Delivery Hero achieved its first- ever positive Group Operating result of €5m and an Adjusted EBITDA of €411m during H125, growing \(71\%\) YoY supported by improved cost efficiency and margin expansion of 70bps YoY to achieve an adj. EBITDA margin at \(1.7\%\) of GMV; 5) Free Cash Flow improved by €96m YoY during H1, resulting in H125 FCF of - €8m; 6) The company maintained a strong cash balance at €2.8bn, following the convertible bond buybacks of €896m during Q1; 7) contingent liabilities have slightly increased (new range €562 and €923m).

Outlook & Guidance: Management has updated its FY25 guidance, with the company now guiding for 1) GMV growth of \(8 - 10\%\) YoY on a like- for- like basis ( \(8 - 10\%\) YoY CCY previously) (vs JPMc/Cons \(+5\% / + 5\%\) reported), 2) total segment revenue growth of \(22 - 24\%\) YoY on a like- for- like basis (from 17- \(19\%\) YoY CCY previously) vs JPMc/Cons \(+17\% / + 16\%\) reported; 3) Adj. EBITDA of €900- 940m (vs JPMc €1,017m and Cons €993m), reduced from previous guided range of €975- 1,025m due to forex headwinds of c.€110m; 4) Free Cash Flow in excess of €120m, (previously €200m) due to forex headwinds of c.€80m. Post the company's disposal of a \(20\%\) share in its Middle Eastern Talabat business we argue that the balance sheet concerns are behind us and we continue to see several levers for Delivery Hero to drive a rapid improvement in profitability (for example a rise in take- rates and scale effects from a larger rider network) which we think is still misunderstood by the market. While we note ongoing debates regarding the company's ability to maintain market share in Korea and Saudi Arabia, we remain overweight given Delivery Hero's attractive valuation as its SOTP shows that at the current price, the company's operations excluding its \(80\%\) stake in Talabat are valued at nil.
Our SOTP based Dec 2026 price target is €35.

Delivery Hero SE (Overweight; Price Target: €35.00)

Post the company's disposal of a \(20\%\) share in its Middle Eastern Talabat business, we argue that the balance sheet concerns are behind us and we continue to see several levers for Delivery Hero to drive a rapid improvement in profitability (for example a rise in take- rates and scale effects from a larger rider network) which we think are still misunderstood by the market. While we note ongoing debates regarding the company's ability to maintain market share in Korea and Saudi Arabia, we remain Overweight given Delivery Hero's attractive valuation, as its SOTP shows that at the current price, the company's operations excluding its \(80\%\) stake in Talabat are valued at nil.
Our SOTP- based Dec 2026 price target is €35.
